    <node id="based on the information provided in the story, it is revealed that the cause of the illness is a contaminated batch of stamps. The clues that lead to this discovery include:&#10;&#10;1. The illness is not communicable, as doctors and dentists are not affected.&#10;2. It is most prevalent in certain cities and less so in rural areas.&#10;3. College students, writers, artists, musicians, and office workers are among those getting sick, while businessmen, teachers, preachers, and government workers (such as postal employees) are not.&#10;4. The illness seems to be related to mail, as a girl from the office who mailed a letter is taken ill, and the lab technician mentions that the contamination may have come from &quot;handling common objects.&quot;&#10;&#10;The story suggests that the protagonist, Andy, discovers the cause of the illness by looking for trends among the different groups affected. He eventually realizes that only those who handle mail or are in close proximity to it are getting sick, and traces the illness back to a batch of stamps that had been contaminated. This is why writers, artists, musicians, and office workers were more likely to be affected, as they are more likely to use and handle stamps than other professions." />
